posts.cooked:
Hello,

I am trying to speed up our constraints in auto get a third coral. I and other programmers have determined that my drive constants need to be tuned better in order to achieve this. I am attempting to use sysID to help with this.

Our team is using Swerve XS with neos / 550s, sparkmaxes, thrifty encoders, and YAGSL . I have used the SwerveDriveTest static method command like so:

The drive runs the routine as intended, with the robot driving forward, back, forward, back, and the second two tests reaching a higher velocity and traveling a farther distance. This tracks with the routines I have observed online.

However, I am having trouble with the logs in SysID. I am using AdvantageScope to download the logs from my Rio, and then opening them in SysID, where I would then drag sysid-test-state-SwerveSubsystem and a module velocity, position, and voltage. However, I could not view feedforward gains and was met with the following error message: Screenshot 2025-03-31 210433 1902×1080 305 KB

Screenshot 2025-03-31 210433 1902×1080 305 KB

Screenshot 2025-03-31 210433 1902×1080 305 KB

I know the drive ran the four tests, and the bottom left widget seems to show us running them, while the center bottom widget shows us running 2/4. However, the error message claims we only ran the first of the four. Thoughts?

posts.name: Jim Sokoloff
posts.cooked:
Feed-forward is used when compensating for a constant load (gravity against an elevator as a common example).

You don’t have any such load in a steer or drive * motor in swerve, so the correctly tuned value for feed-forward is 0.

*Edit: I’m an idiot.

posts.name: Tim Winters
posts.cooked: Feedforward can be used anywhere that you can model the system. If you want to drive the drivetrain at a specific speed, you will need to apply some voltage. SysId will help you model your system so that you can apply that modeled voltage as the feedforward

posts.name: Eli Barnett
posts.cooked:
The presence of an external load is a sufficient but not necessary condition for the usefulness of a feedforward.

An unloaded flywheel under velocity control still (typically) wants a feedforward.

posts.name: Eli Barnett

TheWiz:

Our team had the same issue I don’t remember how we fixed it but it gave really bad values and messed all of our autos.

For what it’s worth, you should never be blindly plugging sysid values into your code and then running an autonomous routine with them. Always check diagnostics and units first.
